                <statement>
                    <p>Find the slope-intercept form of the equation of the line that passes through the points <m>\left(-3,\frac{3}{4}\right)</m> and <m>\left(-6,-\frac{17}{4}\right)</m>.</p>
                    <p><var name="$eq" evaluator="$ev" width="10" /></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>First find the slope through our points: <m>\left(-3,\frac{3}{4}\right)</m> and <m>\left(-6,-\frac{17}{4}\right)</m>. For this problem, we choose to do all of our algebra with improper fractions as it often simplifies the process.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>m\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\substitute{-\frac{17}{4}}-\substitute{\frac{3}{4}}}{\substitute{-6}-\substitute{(-3)}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{-20}{4}}{-3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-5}{-3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{5}{3}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                    <p>So far we have <m>y=\frac{5}{3}x+b</m>. Now we need to solve for <m>b</m> since neither of the points given were the vertical intercept. Recall that to do this, we will choose one of the two points and plug it into our equation. We choose <m>\left(-3,\frac{3}{4}\right)</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{5}{3}x+b</mrow>
                        <mrow>\substitute{\frac{3}{4}}\amp=\frac{5}{3}(\substitute{-3})+b</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{3}{4}\amp=-5+b</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{3}{4}\addright{5}\amp=-5+b\addright{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{3}{4}+\frac{20}{4}\amp=b</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{23}{4}\amp=b</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                    <p>Lastly, we write our equation. <me>y=\frac{5}{3}x+\frac{23}{4}</me></p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
